rman <i>vrī</i> ‘free, independent’. This surname is also found in Hungary, Poland, and especially in France (Alsace and Lorraine). Compare   Free   and   Frei  .","English: variant of   Fray  .","History: This surname (see 1 above) is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."],"variants":[{"name":"Frei","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Otto, Franz, Alois, Erwin, Dieter, Ernst, Ewald, Hedwig, Heinz, Hermann, Juerg.","Swiss German and German: status name for a free man in the feudal system, a variant of   Frey  . This surname is also found in Hungary, Czechia, and France (Alsace and Lorraine). Compare   Free  ."]},{"name":"Fray","meanings":["German: rare variant of   Frey   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this.","English: from the personal name <i>Fray</i>, probably an Anglo-Norman French form of ancient Germanic <i>Fredo</i> (a pet form of names beginning with <i>Fred-</i> or <i>Freth-</i>), which was used by the Normans in Normandy.","English: nickname for a violent person, from Middle English <i>fray</i>, a shortened form of Middle English (Old French) <i>affrai</i> ‘attack, brawl, uproar’."]},{"name":"Frie","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Friedrich, Ulrike, Wolfgang.","German: variant of   Frey  ."]},{"name":"Freye","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt.","German: variant of   Frey  ."]},{"name":"Free","meanings":["English: nickname or status name from Middle English <i>fre</i> ‘free’ (Old English <i>frēo</i>), with reference to either tenurial status (‘free born’) or to character (‘noble, generous, open-handed’).","Irish: variant of   Freeman  .","Americanized form of Swiss German and German   Frei   and   Frey  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":4,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"William Frey was born in 1333, in Staffordshire, England. He married Katherine Haller. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1354, at the age of 21."},"et":{"1333–1354":"1333–1354","1328–Female":"1328–Surnud","1350–1419":"1350–1419","Abt 1350":"umbes 1350","1337":"1337","1333":"1333","1354":"1354","1453":"1453","1350":"1350","1419":"1419","1328":"1328","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England"},"fi":{"1333–1354":"1333–1354","1328–Female":"1328–Kuollut","1350–1419":"1350–1419","Abt 1350":"noin 1350","1337":"1337","1333":"1333","1354":"1354","1453":"1453","1350":"1350","1419":"1419","1328":"1328","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England"},"fr":{"1333–1354":"1333–1354","1328–Female":"1328–Décédée","1350–1419":"1350–1419","Abt 1350":"environ 1350","1337":"1337","1333":"1333","1354":"1354","1453":"1453","1350":"1350","1419":"1419","1328":"1328","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"William Frey est né en 1333, à Staffordshire, Angleterre. Il a épousé Katherine Haller. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé en 1354, à l’âge de 21 ans."},"de":{"1333–1354":"1333–1354","1